To define a custom particle class that adds mass and velocity attributes on top of `ParticleBase`, you should create a derived class from `ParticleBase` and add your custom attributes as instances of `ParticleAttribute<T>`. You also need to add these attributes to the base class in the constructor. Here is an example:

```cpp
class CustomParticles : public ParticleBase<ParticleSpatialLayout<double, 3>> {
public:
    // Attributes for this class
    ParticleAttribute<double> mass;  // mass attribute
    particle_position_type vel;      // velocity attribute, same storage type as R

    // Constructor: add attributes to base class
    CustomParticles(ParticleSpatialLayout<double, 3>* L) : ParticleBase(L) {
        addAttribute(mass);
        addAttribute(vel);
    }
};
```

This example defines a `CustomParticles` class with 3D position and two additional attributes: mass (a double) and velocity (a 3D vector).

